@inproceedings{ashkenazi-2025-d2cs,
    title = "{D}2{CS} - Documents Graph Clustering using {LLM} supervision",
    author = "Ashkenazi, Yoel  and
      Harari, Etzion  and
      Imra, Regev Yehezkel  and
      Abudarham, Naphtali  and
      Cohen, Dekel  and
      Louzoun, Yoram",
    editor = "Christodoulopoulos, Christos  and
      Chakraborty, Tanmoy  and
      Rose, Carolyn  and
      Peng, Violet",
    booktitle = "Findings of the Association for Computational Linguistics: EMNLP 2025",
    month = nov,
    year = "2025",
    address = "Suzhou, China",
    publisher = "Association for Computational Linguistics",
    url = "https://aclanthology.org/2025.findings-emnlp.1283/",
    doi = "10.18653/v1/2025.findings-emnlp.1283",
    pages = "23606--23623",
    ISBN = "979-8-89176-335-7",
    abstract = "Knowledge discovery from large-scale, heterogeneous textual corpora presents a significant challenge. Document clustering offers a practical solution by organizing unstructured texts into coherent groups based on content and thematic similarity. However, clustering does not inherently ensure thematic consistency. Here, we propose a novel framework that constructs a similarity graph over document embeddings and applies iterative graph-based clustering algorithms to partition the corpus into initial clusters. To overcome the limitations of conventional methods in producing semantically consistent clusters, we incorporate iterative feedback from a large language model (LLM) to guide the refinement process. The LLM is used to assess cluster quality and adjust edge weights within the graph, promoting better intra-cluster cohesion and inter-cluster separation. The LLM guidance is based on a set of success Rate metrics that we developed to measure the semantic coherence of clusters. Experimental results on multiple benchmark datasets demonstrate that the iterative process and additional user-supplied a priori edges improve the summaries' consistency and fluency, highlighting the importance of known connections among the documents. The removal of very rare or very frequent sentences has a mixed effect on the quality scores.Our full code is available here: \url{https://github.com/D2CS-sub/D2CS}"
}

